No, that doesn't explain it at all. If you play a radio with 50us
de-emphasis on stations with 75us pre-emphasis (Euro radios being used in
the US) the only thing that happens is the high frequencies sound a bit
brighter. This can easily be confirmed with an FM tuner that has a built in
switch for de-emphasis. Switch from 75 to 50, and the top end gets a little
brighter. That's all.  That doesn't explain the thumpiness of some of the
German radios, which I attribute to the huge amount of compression along
with artificial bass boost so common in most FM signals today. Those German
sets all had loudness taps with aggressive bass boost, especially at lower
volumes. When those radios were new, radio stations had lower modulation
levels, and far less compression. Volume controls would be set higher for
equivalent perceived volume, thereby reducing the loudness compensation in
the radio. I also think detectors are being overloaded in some of these
radios with today's signals. These radios never had very flat response. They
were &quot;tweaked&quot; to sound &quot;good&quot;.
