The Gates transmitters of the 1950s were spec'ed down to 50 Hz, not 100
Hz.  Full modulation capability down to 50 Hz was an FCC requirement for
FM transmitters.  The reason they didn't go deeper was because the Gates
transmitters used Phase Modulators, not Frequency Modulators.  Gates
replaced the single phase modulator with what they dubbed the &quot;Cascade&quot;
modulator which was two phase modulators in series.  I'm not sure when
they came out with this improvement, probably the late 1950s, but it
should have approximately doubled (halved?) the low frequency
performance.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; With Optimod processing and newer equipment, you can spec
&gt; down to 2 Hz. And yeah, Rock and Hip Hop station formats are the
&gt; worst offenders for bass boost. Got'ta get that thump in there.
">

I'm not sure how the Optimod contributes to getting down to 2 Hz?  The
major contributor to this is probably the digital NCOs that replaced the
old analog VCOs with their PLLs and loop filters, which had previously
replaced the Phase Modulators Gates used.  I guess RCA's direct FM
system was on the right track in the late 1930s, Armstrong got that
wrong.

