Hi Jeff,

It was at least half a year ago that you were doing that modeling, if
the loudness control curve is a big part of the problem I am surprised
that you haven't come up with a new curve yet.  The loudness circuit
typically only involves a single resistor and capacitor, and I can't
imagine any part of the radio that would be easier to modify.  Try some
other R and C values until you find something you like.  I would
probably add a second resistor to the circuit so that the high frequency
gain vs. volume control position wouldn't be changed.

If the problem is that we are no longer plagued with the poor modulation
performance of the old Gates FM transmitters, as you were speculating,
then a simple attenuator in the FM audio path should remedy the problem.
This could be as simple as adding a resistor to the band switch that
would be in series with the top of the volume control in the FM mode.

As far as Lou's suggestion of a 30 Hz high pass filter goes, I suspect
that is not likely to be of much help because the Optimod already
includes a high pass filter with the corner at about 30 Hz.  A more
likely problem is that the Optimod includes a bass equalizer, I will
have to look it up to be sure of the exact parameters, but IIRC it peaks
the bass somewhere around 100 Hz.  To counter this a rolloff starting
much higher than 30 Hz would be needed, perhaps a simple 6 dB/octave
rolloff starting at 150 or 200 Hz would be appropriate.

Regards,

John Byrns

